03930nam a22006735i 9780271061238DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710612387 a10.1515/97802710612382doi  a(DE-B1597)583827  a(OCoLC)1262307765  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a305.420109732231 aGardner, Catherine Villanueva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpowerment and Interconnectivity :bToward a Feminist History of Utilitarian Philosophy /cCatherine Villanueva Gardner. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Empowerment and Interconnectivity -- t1 Wheeler and Thompson: The Appeal and the Problem of Empowerment -- t2 Catharine Beecher and writing philosophy for women -- t3 Frances Wright: Interconnectivity and Synthesis -- t4 Tea and Sympathy with John Stuart Mill -- tConclusion and Next Steps -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFeminist history of philosophy has successfully focused thus far on canon revision, canon critique, and the recovery of neglected or forgotten women philosophers. However, the methodology remains underexplored, and it seems timely to ask larger questions about how the history of philosophy is to be done and whether there is, or needs to be, a specifically feminist approach to the history of philosophy. In Empowerment and Interconnectivity, Catherine Gardner examines the philosophy of three neglected women philosophers, Catharine Beecher, Frances Wright, and Anna Doyle Wheeler, all of whom were British or American utilitarian philosophers of one stripe or another. Gardner’s focus in this book is less on accounting for the neglect or disappearance of these women philosophers and more on those methodological (or epistemological) questions we need to ask in order to recover their philosophy and categorize it as feminist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFeminist theoryzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aFeminist theoryzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUtilitarianismzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aUtilitarianismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271061238?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271061238423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271061238/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK